\pard\f0\fs28  Variable; there are marked differences between plants at the western and eastern ends of the European range. In the east the bracteoles are strongly saccate at the base, broadly rounded to emarginate at the apex and often twice as wide as long, the corolla is 55-90 mm and the stamens (25-)28-36(-39) mm. In the west (N.W. Italy, S.E. France and Spain) the bracteoles are much less strongly saccate, obtuse to subacute and about as long as wide, the corolla is 50-65 mm and the stamens 24-28(-30) mm. There seems, however, to be not quite sufficient morphological or geographical discontinuity to recognize subspecies.
